{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491297"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.25,0.15,0.48,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49052"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/907"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34080"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49052"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner after an episode of rapid onset, sharp right upper quadrant pain that lasted for about 20 minutes and then subsided. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min and blood pressure 140/100 mmHg. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. The practitioner arranges a non-contrast CT scan (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately reflects the CT findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A hydatid cyst","Gallstones","Chronic pancreatitis","Abdominal aortic aneurysm","Renal calculus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E with a rim of calcification in the vessel wall. His age and sex put him at risk of aneurysm formation. Bearing in mind the patient\u0027s symptoms on presentation to his local doctor, this radiological finding is incidental. Most abdominal aortic aneurysms are asymptomatic and are detected on imaging for other indications. Because of its size it cannot be ignored and the patient will require regular surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid cyst \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely given it is not involving the liver, lungs or spleen, which are the most common intra-abdominal sites for cyst formation. Hydatid cysts may contain calcified borders in up to 30% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstones\u003C/strong\u003E are not suggested by this CT. Only some types of gallstones appear on CT, and ultrasound is a quicker, cheaper, more accurate imaging choice that does not expose the patient to radiation, making it the investigation of choice for suspected gallstones. This particular slice is well below the anatomical level of the gallbladder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic pancreatitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis not suggested by this CT. Features of chronic pancreatitis on CT include pancreatic duct dilation, pancreatic calcification, and pancreatic atrophy. This CT slice is below the anatomical level of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost types of \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal calculus \u003C/strong\u003Eare visible on CT scan. These are usually observed lodged in the vesicoureteric junction, which is not visualised here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal aortic aneurysms are often asymptomatic but must be recognised when present on imaging."],"references":["Aggarwal S, Qamar A, Sharma V, Sharma A. Abdominal aortic aneurysm: A comprehensive review. Exp Clin Cardiol. 2011 Spring;16(1):11-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3076160/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34080"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16392"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20888"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16392"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/708a5fbd-8f02-4ec3-a41f-3eb3424420a4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/708a5fbd-8f02-4ec3-a41f-3eb3424420a4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":385}},{"type":"media","id":"20888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20888"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/n4lR75xJsUIrMP8lGetE20eIQDo8L2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/n4lR75xJsUIrMP8lGetE20eIQDo8L2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":385}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34080"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T22:48:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T20:36:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49052"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,